From: FlareSolverr Stealth Migration
Subject: [PATCH 7/7] Remove HeadlessChrome UA token when running headless

When Chrome runs with --headless, it inserts "HeadlessChrome" into
the product string, replacing "Chrome". This is the most direct
bot-detection signal and forces FlareSolverr to issue an
Emulation.setUserAgentOverride CDP call after launch to clean it up.

That CDP call has two problems:
  1. There is a race window between browser start and the CDP call
     during which any JS that runs can see the HeadlessChrome token.
  2. The full userAgentMetadata (platform, architecture, brands) must
     be reconstructed in Python from a UA string parse, which is
     fragile.

This patch suppresses the HeadlessChrome product override so the
browser natively presents the same UA string as regular Chrome.
navigator.userAgentData is also natively consistent because its
brands and platform are derived from the same build configuration,
not from the headless mode flag.

--- a/chrome/browser/headless/headless_mode_util.cc
+++ b/chrome/browser/headless/headless_mode_util.cc
@@ -40,9 +40,10 @@ void SetUpHeadlessMode() {
   DCHECK(IsHeadlessMode());

   // Set up the page visibility state for background tabs.
   blink::SetDomainRelaxationForbiddenForURLScheme(true, "file");
-
-  // Override the user agent product to identify headless sessions.
-  content::SetBrowserClientUserAgentProduct("HeadlessChrome");
+
+  // Intentionally omitted: SetBrowserClientUserAgentProduct("HeadlessChrome").
+  // Presenting as regular Chrome avoids the most direct bot-detection signal.
+  // FlareSolverr's --preload-script handles any remaining JS-level UA patches.

   SetUpHeadlessBrowserOriginTrials();
 }
